The impact of El Ni√±o on the Species Composition of Genera Amphiprion and Lutjanus in Australia

R12241209 Lin, Ting-Chang, R12241202 Chang, Hsin-Yu, R12241206 Liu, Li-Hsuan

2023-12-08

Introduction

In this project, we manipulated the ‚ÄòIMOS - National Reef Monitoring Network Sub-Facility - Global reef fish abundance and biomass‚Äô data set from Systematic global assessment of reef fish communities by the Reef Life Survey program. After manipulating the data, we observed that most of it was collected around Australia. Thus, we decided to restrict our survey area in Australia. We identified two genera, Amphiprion and Hypoplectrodes, which are distributed in the northern and southern coastal areas of Australia, respectively. We chose to compare the species composition of Amphiprion and Hypoplectrodes during El Ni√±o years and normal years to assess if El Ni√±o has different impacts on tropical and subtropical genera.

Yet, after calculating the number of individuals of Hypoplectrodes in different years, we discovered a dominant species, Hypoplectrodes maccullochi, within the genus Hypoplectrodes around Australia. Recognizing that the test of homogeneity would be inefficient in this case, we decided to shift our focus and compare the species composition of Amphiprion and Lutjanus. Both genera have sufficient survey data in this dataset.

‚Ä¢El Ni√±o

During El Ni√±o years, the weakening of trade winds causes the North Pacific warm pool to shift toward the east side. As a result, the surface seawater temperature (SST) around Australia will be lower than normal. We expect this difference in SST will have impacts on species composition of tropical and subtropical genera to different extent. (https://geographical.co.uk/science-environment/geo-explainer-el-nino)

‚Ä¢The optimal temperature for Amphiprion, Hypoplectrodes and Lutjanus

Amphiprion: For the well-researched A. ocellaris, the optimal temperature is said to be around 29‚ÑÉ or 30‚ÑÉ (Soman et al., 2021; Velasco et al., 2019). Hypoplectrodes: According to FishBase (https://www.fishbase.se/search.php), the dominant species in Australia, H. maccullochi, has a preferred temperature range of 17.3‚ÑÉ to 24.7‚ÑÉ. Lutjanus: There are abundant species in this genus, so we can only generalize their preferred temperature range to be between 18‚ÑÉ and 29‚ÑÉ.

‚Ä¢Hypothesis

H0: The species composition of Amphiprion and Lutjanus during El Ni√±o years and normal years shows no differences.

H1: The species composition of Amphiprion and Lutjanus during El Ni√±o years and normal years shows differences.

However, we thought that used direct observation numbers to test if there was a significant change between these two years was too subjective. Then we used the observation number divided by the survey number to calculate each species‚Äô density.

Amphiprion_2019_2016 <- rbind(Amphiprion_2019_species_7, Amphiprion_2016_species_7)

#species number/ survey number= density
Amphiprion_2019_2016[year=="2019", density:= (species_number/nrow(Amphiprion_2019))]
Amphiprion_2019_2016[year=="2016", density:= (species_number/nrow(Amphiprion_2016))]

#The value of density is a little bit low, so we use log for transformation.
Amphiprion_2019_2016[,log:= log(density)]

Use two sample t-test and Fligner-Killeen test to test if species composition are significant different between 2016 and 2019.

#Two sample t-test
t.test(Amphiprion_2019_2016$density~Amphiprion_2019_2016$year)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Amphiprion_2019_2016$density by Amphiprion_2019_2016$year
## t = -0.7199, df = 7.3204, p-value = 0.4939
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group 2016 and group 2019 is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -3.459913  1.833906
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 2016 mean in group 2019 
##          0.5924908          1.4054945
#Fligner-Killeen test
fligner.test (Amphiprion_2019_2016$density~Amphiprion_2019_2016$year)
## 
##  Fligner-Killeen test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  Amphiprion_2019_2016$density by Amphiprion_2019_2016$year
## Fligner-Killeen:med chi-squared = 0.076631, df = 1, p-value = 0.7819

Both p-value are higher than 0.05, so reject our H1 hypothesis.

Next we make another bar plot to see the density difference between 2016 to 2019 on different species.

Result & Discussion

In the Australian marine region, the density of different species in the genus Amphiprion showed no difference between the years 2016 and 2019 (two sample t-test p = 0.4939, Fligner-Killeen test of homogeneity p = 0.7819). While the density of different species in the genus Lutjanus also had no difference between 2016 and 2019 (two sample t-test p = 0.755, Fligner-Killeen test of homogeneity p = 0.5737). These results reject our hypothesis that El Ni√±o and normal years would have differences in genus compositions.

With the unexpected result, we present several possibilities to explain it as much as possible. First, we found out that although 2016 was recorded to have the most dramatic El Ni√±o event in recent years, it surprisingly had higher sea surface temperature (SST) in Australia compared with 2019. This fact may be evidence that the climate change impact on SST was already overtaking the El Ni√±o event, which led to abnormal SST changes under El Ni√±o and normal years. Therefore, when climate change disturbs the effect of El Ni√±o, the impact on these research genera may be neutralized or intensified.

#reference: ‚Äúhttp://www.bom.gov.au/climate/current/annual/aus/2016/#tabs=Sea-surface-temperature‚Äù

#reference: ‚Äúhttp://www.bom.gov.au/climate/current/annual/aus/2019/#tabs=Sea-surface-temperature‚Äù

Second, to understand the impact of El Ni√±o, we chose 2016 (El Ni√±o year) and 2019 (relatively normal year) with enough genus and species data. However, the time between these two years may not be long enough for the composition of these genera to change. In other words, the genus composition would not change dramatically between these two years. Third, according to the dataset description, the resources of the dataset came from different collaboration memberships. One of the biggest problems was the method of recording the fish, it depended on the diving and recording skills of marine scientists and divers, and other partnerships. With non-specific members, timing, and location, could lead to various biases in fish abundance and affect the research result.

To gain a more specific understanding of the changes in genus composition, two plots illustrating changes in species density were presented. The result showed that both genera (Amphiprion and Lutjanus) did not have specific change patterns between 2016 and 2019. The possible reason is that these two genera have similar habitat preferences, which are both largely distributed in tropical and sub-tropical oceans. Therefore, they might have similar responses to environmental change, but unfortunately, there were no significant changes can be found in our research (some species‚Äô densities increase, others decrease in both genera).
